The product team wants to launch "Pages You May Like" — but before any ML model gets involved, they want to know: 
can we build a baseline recommendation purely from our existing friend graph and follow data?

##You are given the list of Facebook friends and the list of Facebook pages that users follow.
Your task is to create a new recommendation system for Facebook.
For each Facebook user, find pages that this user doesn't follow but at least one of their friends does.
Output the user ID and the ID of the page that should be recommended to this user.


with pagemapping as (
select f.user_id,f.friend_id,p.page_id
from users_friends f
join users_pages p
on f.friend_id = p.user_id
)
select distinct o.user_id, o.page_id
from pagemapping o
left join users_pages p1
on o.user_id = p1.user_id
and o.page_id = p1.page_id
where p1.user_id is null


My approach:

→ Built a mapping of every user to the pages their friends follow
→ Used a LEFT JOIN back to the user's own follows to find pages they don't already have
→ Added DISTINCT to collapse duplicates from multiple friends following the same page


First attempt filtered with page_id <> p1.page_id instead of an anti-join. It looked right but only checked that one row differed — not that every row differed. A user following 5 pages could still get recommended a page they already follow, because some other row happened to not match. Switched to LEFT JOIN + IS NULL, which checks across all rows at once instead of row-by-row.
The insight: the candidate set here isn't the finished feature — it's the raw material. Every pair returned is a page with at least one friend's social proof behind it, with zero modeling required. The real product question sits one layer up: do you show all candidates, or rank by how many friends follow each page first?
Interview Framing

"I actually shipped a subtle bug here on my first pass — filtering with <> instead of an anti-join. 
It returns almost the right answer, which is what makes it dangerous: <> only proves one row differs, but 'not following' requires proving no row matches. 
That's the kind of mistake that passes a quick eyeball check and fails in production."
